    q: "How much does a specialty office coffee program cost per month?",
    a: "A specialty office coffee program for a 50-person office using roughly 5–8 lbs of coffee per week runs $70–$120 per week in coffee cost, or $280–$480 per month. That's $5–10 per employee per month — a benefit cost that's among the lowest on the books and one of the most consistently appreciated by staff. Scale up or down proportionally based on headcount and consumption habits."
  },
  {
    q: "What equipment does an office need for specialty coffee?",
    a: "A quality commercial batch brewer — Fetco, Bunn, or Wilbur Curtis — is the standard for most office environments. It's reliable, produces consistent quality at volume, and doesn't require a dedicated operator. For offices that want something more premium, a built-in grinder and a semi-automatic espresso machine can work if someone is willing to be accountable for maintenance and calibration. Avoid single-serve pod machines if quality is the goal — the economics are poor and the cup quality caps out well below what a basic batch brewer can produce."
  },
  {
    q: "Should an office buy coffee from a local or national roaster?",
    a: "For most offices, a local roaster is the better choice — faster delivery means fresher coffee, in-person support is more available, and the local sourcing story resonates with employees who care about it. National roasters with strong B2B programs can serve offices well when local options are limited or when the office has multiple locations that benefit from a single supplier relationship."
  },
  {
    q: "How often should office coffee be replenished?",
    a: "Weekly is standard for most specialty wholesale office programs. Coffee is at its best 7–21 days after roast, so a weekly replenishment cycle ensures employees are always drinking fresh coffee rather than something that's been sitting in the cabinet for a month. Many specialty roasters who serve office accounts offer standing weekly orders that ship on a fixed schedule — set it once and don't think about it."
